g? Or, is all \n&gt; the action happening outside of atman? Is ther=\r\ne anything outside of \n&gt; atman at all?\n&gt; \n&gt; Some buddhist philosophies coin=\r\ned the term anatman (non-Self) to \n&gt; describe transient things. But, in Ved=\r\nic philosophy, there is no \n&gt; anatman. All that is is atman (Self). Ocean i=\r\ns permanent and still, but \n&gt; ripples that arise in it are transient and mo=\r\nving. But ripples are part \n&gt; of ocean only and you do not start labeling r=\r\nipples as &quot;non-ocean&quot;.\n&gt; \n&gt; Atman or Purusha or Shiva is the potential ener=\r\ngy of this cosmos, while \n&gt; Maya or Prakriti or Shakti is the kinetic energ=\r\ny of this cosmos. Shiva \n&gt; and Shakti are seen as different entities by som=\r\ne people, but rishis \n&gt; have declared their oneness. Potential energy becom=\r\nes kinetic energy and \n&gt; vice versa.\n&gt; \n&gt; Atman is the still ocean and Maya=\r\n is the force (kinetic) that gives rise \n&gt; to moving ripples on the surface=\r\n. A ripple that exerts itself to move in \n&gt; a particular way keeps collidin=\r\ng with the force and keeps moving hither \n&gt; and tither in a chaotic way for=\r\n a very long time. A ripple that does not \n&gt; exert itself and moves smoothl=\r\ny as dictated by the force will eventually \n&gt; grind to a halt and cease to =\r\nexist as a ripple on the surface. It then \n&gt; becomes part of the still ocea=\r\nn. If a ripple exerts itself to become \n&gt; still, it may even take longer to=\r\n become still. What prolongs a ripple \n&gt; is not movement but resisting the =\r\ndirection given by the force and \n&gt; exerting to move in a particular way (o=\r\nr even exerting to become still). \n&gt; A ripple that surrenders to the force =\r\nwill ride the course and die down \n&gt; faster.\n&gt; \n&gt; Contemplate the imagery I=\r\n presented above regarding Atman and Maya, \n&gt; ignorant/egoistic action and =\r\ndetached action! It is very apt.\n&gt; \n&gt; *        *        *\n&gt; \n&gt; In not-so-di=\r\nstant past, sannyasins remained in ashrams and isolated \n&gt; themselves from =\r\nsociety and did their sadhana. Swami Vivekananda started \n&gt; a new trend.\n&gt; =\r\n\n&gt; A sannyasin renounces expectation of things from people stuck in \n&gt; tran=\r\nsient material world and does not depend on anyone. But he may still \n&gt; *gi=\r\nve* basic material things to those hapless people stuck in transient \n&gt; mat=\r\nerial world! For example, Swami Vivekananda and his brother monks \n&gt; went t=\r\no places struck by plague, floods, droughts, cyclones etc and \n&gt; served peo=\r\nple. They provided food, medicines etc (instead of lecturing \n&gt; that body i=\r\ns a transient illusion and one should stop worrying about its \n&gt; welfare!) =\r\nand also did construction work. They ignored the welfare of \n&gt; their own bo=\r\ndies, put themselves at risk and overcame maya personally. \n&gt; But they serv=\r\ned those still stuck in maya without looking down upon them \n&gt; or their nee=\r\nds or maya that trapped them! Those who wanted food got \n&gt; food, those who =\r\nwanted medicines got medicines and those who wanted \n&gt; books got books. Ren=\r\nunciation means you do not expect anything from \n&gt; anyone and accept whatev=\r\ner comes to you naturally. It does not \n&gt; necessarily mean rejecting or ign=\r\noring others. Overcoming maya does not \n&gt; require belittling maya or belitt=\r\nling those still stuck in maya.\n&gt; \n&gt; The trend started by Swami Vivekananda=\r\n was continued by Swami Sivananda. \n&gt; For that reason, it is a bit weird to=\r\n see him talking so ill of action! \n&gt; He was obviously trying to inspire a =\r\nspecific group of people for a \n&gt; specific body of work. These words are ne=\r\nither universal nor do they \n&gt; reflect his tremendous wisdom I have seen el=\r\nsewhere!\n&gt; \n&gt; *        *        *\n&gt; \n&gt; All this intellectual discussion may=\r\n be satisfying to some, but the \n&gt; quote from Swami Brahmanananda in the ot=\r\nher mail is very apt: &quot;You have \n&gt; been only hearing of all these spiritual=\r\n things. Now realise them. You \n&gt; have done enough study and reasoning. Now=\r\n do some spiritual practice. \n&gt; First take up that aspect of God which appe=\r\nals to you most. Follow your \n&gt; own path of Sadhana. When you realise God t=\r\nhrough it, you will feel the \n&gt; joy of realising Him also in other aspects =\r\nand through other paths.&quot;\n&gt; \n&gt; According to Ramakrishna, Swami Brahmananda =\r\nwas a gopala who accompanied \n&gt; Lord Krishna in a previous life. His words =\r\nare simple, pragmatic and \n&gt; powerful.\n&gt; \n&gt; I want this forum to facilitate=\r\n exchange of Vedic knowledge (and I will \n&gt; also be contributing, though in=\r\n spurts). But I want more that this forum \n&gt; should inspire people to do sa=\r\ndhana and find God. In the end, that is \n&gt; what matters.\n&gt; \n&gt; Best regards,=\r\n\n&gt; Narasimha\n&gt; ----------------------------------------------------------\n&gt;=\r\n    Free Jyotish Software, Free Jyotish Lessons, Jyotish Writings,\n&gt; &quot;Do It=\r\n Yourself&quot; ritual manuals for short Homam and Pitri Tarpana:\n&gt; http://www.V=\r\nedicAstrologer.org\n&gt;       Films that make a difference: http://SaraswatiFi=\r\nlms.org\n&gt;       Spirituality: http://groups.yahoo.com/group/vedic-wisdom\n&gt; =\r\n   Jyotish writings: http://groups.yahoo.com/group/JyotishWritings\n&gt;       =\r\n                Twitter ID: @homam108\n&gt; -----------------------------------=\r\n-----------------------\n&gt; \n&gt; On Mon, Jun 20, 2011 at 2:31 PM, Krishnendu wr=\r\note:\n&gt; \n&gt;      Some may say: =C3=A2From. this it follows that it is not nec=\r\nessary for \n&gt; a knower even to serve his preceptor or to perform tapas.=C3=\r\n=A2 \n&gt; Householders who are afraid of begging for bread and are afraid of \n=\r\n&gt; ridicule argue like this through their sharp intelligence. You cannot \n&gt; =\r\nsay that even begging for bread is a binding rule on a sannyasin. That \n&gt; i=\r\ns not a desire and the sannyasin is virtually a mendicant without rules \n&gt; =\r\nbinding him. He is not liable to any kind of command. Even one who does \n&gt; =\r\nnot know Brahman but who is desirous of emancipation should enter into \n&gt; t=\r\nhe order of a sannyasin. The sruti says: =C3=A2Let one live in the order \n&gt;=\r\n of sannyasa which is a means to the knowledge of Brahman.=C3=A2 \n&gt; Brahmac=\r\nharya may help one to attain knowledge but it is not the case \n&gt; with a hou=\r\nseholder. When a means is not properly followed it can never \n&gt; accomplish =\r\nany object. The heavenly bliss of the karma-kandin is only a \n&gt; form of wor=\r\nldly enjoyment. Heaven is only another world. If one \n&gt; professes to have k=\r\nnowledge he cannot do actions, for actions are \n&gt; worldly. The atman is ent=\r\nirely opposed to action and hence it cannot be \n&gt; an auxiliary to the knowl=\r\nedge of it. The sruti says: =C3=A2When to him \n&gt; everything has become the =\r\nSelf, who should see what and through what \n&gt; should one see?=C3=A2 etc. Th=\r\nis nullifies the meaning of actions in one who \n&gt; has knowledge.\n&gt;\n\n\n \r\n--0-2121644821-1308697751=:38466\r\nContent-Type: text/html; charset=utf-8\r\nContent-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable\r\n\r\n&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;style type=3D&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;&lt;!-- DIV {margin:0px;} --&gt;&lt;/style&gt;&lt;/he=\r\nad&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;div style=3D&quot;font-family:times new roman,new york,times,serif;fon=\r\nt-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;\nNamaste Anoop,&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;br&gt;Interesting\n you ask this question=\r\n about vairagya! Swami Sivananda has written an \nentire book on this subjec=\r\nt, &quot;How to get Vairagya&quot;!&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;a rel=3D&quot;nofollow&quot; target=3D&q